    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>San Francisco</placeName>
                <date>July 7<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1862</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dr Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Yesterdays mail<lb/> brought me a letter from my son who<lb/> is one
                of the surgeons in the United States<lb/> Navy in which he mentions that He had<lb/>
                an introduction to you by <persName>Dr Fischel.</persName> I<lb/> hope the interview
                was mutually agreeable<lb/> on his part I can answer for from the tone<lb/> in which
                he writes you being brought to mind<lb/> in this way I thought I would drop a
                few<lb/> lines, altho' I have nothing very particular<lb/> to relate. Religious
                matters are at the stand<lb/> excepting that the Emanuel go on with<lb/> their
                reforms, and their Rabbi is laboring<lb/> hard to set at <sic>nought</sic> all
                Orthodox <del>Refor</del><lb/> forms and ceremonies. In a recent discourse<lb/> of
                his he stated that cutting the <add>קריעה</add> over the<lb/>
                <add>שבעה</add> is out of date and wearing the Beard<lb/> in the <add>קרעו לבבכם ואל
                    בגדתם</add> is absurd. The <add>?</add> preached<lb/>
                <add>בר מצוה</add> that is the real meaning<lb/> said the Preacher. I was not
                present—but</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>such was the general reports. It is pitiful<lb/> to relate how our sacred ceremonies
                are being<lb/> undermined. It is currently reported that a<lb/> father brought his
                son to be taught the requisites<lb/> for his <add>תפלין</add> but the Dr refused to
                teach<lb/> him to say <add>קהלה</add> stating all was nonsense<lb/> I am however
                steadfast in my Orthodox<lb/> course and I am happy to say my <add>מצות</add><lb/>
                are firm with me. That is one satisfaction to me<lb/> it was noticed last year that
                our <add>שחיטה</add> were<lb/> not as they should be. I <add>?</add> myself
                this<lb/> year in the matter, and formed a party to<lb/> do as the Law directs and
                the result proved<lb/> as you will see by the enclosed Circular.<lb/> It may not be
                of any moment to you so far<lb/> from us but in there perilous times every
                little<lb/> thing is of consequence to uphold the fabric<lb/> from falling into
                ruin. No doubt you will think<lb/> with me. I hope also to effect a radical
                reform<lb/> in the <add>אבל לא אשר את לבי לדבריהם</add> of Heaven grant me strength
                and<lb/> health. I have to fight the Battle in the good cause<lb/> I am at times
                sneered at being so old fashioned<lb/> and against progress <add>רכב וצלח</add><lb/>
                I say with <persName>David</persName>
                <add>Hebrew</add> and it must be<lb/> so in the end. I amuse myself now when at<lb/>
                leisure in reading your Occident. Will you<lb/> send me by return the following Nos.
                to complete<lb/> Vol. 18 of weekly series &amp; they are: <hi rend="underline"
                    >1-2-3-4-5</hi><lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">20-24-27-40-42</hi> as also the whole volume <hi
                    rend="underline">17</hi><lb/> so that I can bind them and you will oblige</p>
            <p rend="indent(8)">Yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(8)">
                <persName role="author">H. A. Henry</persName>
            </p>
            <p><hi rend="underline">Let me hear from you soon</hi>. </p>
        </body>
    </text>
